{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492344"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:25:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:25:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1037"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1037"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.59,0.12,0.07,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92548"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1037"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75863"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3526"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18579"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31694"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45061"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92548"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman is being investigated for an incidental finding of hypercalcaemia. An elevated serum parathyroid hormone supports a diagnosis of primary hyperparathyroidism, likely caused by a parathyroid adenoma. She has no other health issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her BMI is 34, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, pulse 80/min and temperature 37.2 C. Apart from a full neck and an abdominal pannus, the physical examination is unremarkable. Surgery is planned and the tumour needs to be localised.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neck ultrasound","Technetium-99m sestamibi scintigraphy","Gallium-68 dotatate PET/CT","I-123 Thyroid scintigraphy","FDG-PET scan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is frequently used for localisation of a parathyroid adenoma, however, the accuracy of ultrasound is very operator dependent. \u003Cstrong\u003ESestamibi scintigraphy\u003C/strong\u003E has the highest positive predictive value and is the preferred primary investigation for the localisation of the adenoma. Both techniques are often used for pre-operative localisation, as concordant imaging allows a minimally invasive approach to be used. Apart from operator-dependency, the disadvantages of ultrasound include reduced accuracy with small adenomas, obesity and adenomas outside the usual anatomical fields. 4D CT scan is being increasingly used to localise parathyroid adenomas. Other localisation options include MRI and PET, but these imaging tools are less readily available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroid scintigraphy is used to measure the overall activity of the thyroid gland. Gallium-68 dotatate PET/CT is used for the localisation of neuroendocrine tumours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most common cause for primary hyperparathyroidism is a single parathyroid adenoma","Once the decision to operate is made, pre-operative radiological localisation is performed to facilitate minimally invasive surgery if the imaging is concordnant."],"references":["Bilezikian JP, Bandeira L, Khan A, et al. Hyperparathyroidism. Lancet 2018; 391:168-78."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75863"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1037"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75863"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T10:52:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T10:52:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1037"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92548"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":n